Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California at Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its impact on chemical uniformity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow you to search among the stars related, i.e. those originated from one cluster.
The results of their research were published in the journal Nature, and you can read them briefly on the university’s website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is turbulent mixing in the gas clouds that preceded the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the stellar cluster, by its chemical composition, it is possible to determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the stellar relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulation carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer modeled two streams of interstellar gas that together formed the cloud.
For several million years, this object, under the influence of its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added paint tags to the original gas streams and found that fast turbulent mixing in the cloud achieves a high degree of chemical uniformity.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to search for related stars in chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
