Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis proposed a bill under which the organization of trade unions is protected as a civil right.
“Where unions are, there are middle-class jobs,” said Alison, a Minnesota Democrat who is co-chair of the Progressive Fraction Congress.
That is why I am proud to present the Workers' Rights Enlargement Act along with the symbol of the John Lewis Civil Rights Movement.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal opportunities in discriminating against the organization of trade unions, as in other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of the opponents of trade unions
The amendment of the Labour Relations Act to allow workers who are discriminated against for their participation in the organization of trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and penalties - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is undoubtedly not a radical initiative – at least according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill offer is to remember the very American thought.
Despite the attacks that trade unions have suffered in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states around the country – Americans have once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labour rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country defended at the same time democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to an organization.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hideka Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in the formation of a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly acknowledged that “the right of workers to an organization, to negotiation, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or area of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will not have legal effect; measures aimed at these purposes will be considered unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as an instrument of universal protection, Roosevelt and the composers included the guarantee of the "rights of what to do."
For generations, Americans have taken the basic position that labour rights are human rights.
When this country consulted other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organise trade unions – and that the trade union should participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government institutions – should be.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to an organization and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but has increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions have miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as well.
The official recognition of labour rights as human rights – and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against the organisation of trade unions – have long been ripe.
Kit Allison and John Lewis revive ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
