Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment means that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video in memory of their dead mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women living in rural areas in Australia are at a higher risk of ovarian cancer death than those living in cities.
The researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent survived five years after being diagnosed.
Senior researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute of Medical Research said that the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than in those living in urban areas.
NEW MEDICAMENTS Might Slow Lung Cancer and Ovarian Cancer
Researchers tracked the medical path of women for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the woman’s age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also influenced the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those living in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those living in urban areas.
While the study was not intended to determine why women living outside the city are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that premature diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible facts.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly found in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of outbound services that would allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people passing treatment away from home may help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, emphasizing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Niv, was told that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
