Genetic impairment is often misdiagnosed
The British woman said she had spent many years thinking that she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karen Rogers spent most of her adolescence thinking that she had only lived for a few years after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Sharko-Mari-Tuta disease (SMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that lead to damage to nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
The charity CMT UK reported that misdiagnosed is a common problem among people with SMT because so little is known about this condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have SMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, uncertain walking, and squeezed toes.
Patients may feel dizziness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, which means that the symptoms intensify over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Frederick's (AF) attack, a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she was going to be in a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and she would die before she turned 30.
The mother of two children, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others did.
I fell down every day, and it took me more time.
I could never ride a rollercoaster or skateboard with other kids, and I had a lot of fun at school because I was walking and running.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at the medical card when her doctor left the room, and it was written that she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I pushed my nose to a wrong place, and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library, and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I got the information in response, I was shocked and panicked as much as possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I turn 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in the meantime.
I went through it alone, and I planned my own funerals.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realized that her ability to walk did not deteriorate as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me, and said, "Dearest, I don't think you have this disease because you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you've got something that's a lot less life-threatening.
After a few genetic examinations, she was found to have MST.
“When he explained what the SMT was, I thought I had a happy ticket,” she said.
The UK SMT charity has announced a month of information about SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
