Commenting on the draft law submitted to the State Duma today, Leonid Levin, the first deputy chairman of the Duma Committee on Information Policy, said he saw no problems with the transfer of the date of entry into force of the Personal Data Protection Act.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storages of personal data of Russians in the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "in Rostelekoma", which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent, Ma is ready for sale, and are ready for sale.
“In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
“If companies decide to enforce the law and continue to operate in the territory of the Russian Federation, I don’t see any problems – they will get technological opportunities for hosting,” Levin said.
Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the bill, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that in the event of the adoption of the bill, the Russians will no longer be able to use many global internet services.
In particular, it is about online booking services of airline tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively stipulating that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
