Possible way to steal photos of naked celebrities
Massive star account hacking may be caused by a vulnerability in the Find My Phone app.
The potential scenario of development was described by The Next Web resource.
On the Github resource was published a script in Python, which allowed you to select passwords for Apple’s Find My Phone service.
This service allows you to track the location of your iPhone.
To access it, the same login link and Apple ID password is used as to access the Apple iCloud cloud from which photos of celebrities were stolen.
The script allowed the reset method to recognize the password from Find My Phone.
This method introduces all sorts of combinations of characters, starting with the most frequently used passwords.
The author of the script claimed that the number of password options entered in Find My Phone is unlimited.
With the correct organization of the security system after several unsuccessful attempts to enter the wrong password the account should be blocked and notify the user of the attempted hacking.
Due to the vulnerability, users have not received any notifications of an attempt to retrieve a password to their account.
The hackers recognized the password from Apple ID and used it to access iCloud.
According to Twitter user Hackapp, the vulnerability was detected two days ago, on Saturday, and a scripting program for selecting passwords was written to it.
The vulnerability is currently closed: after five attempts, access to the service is blocked.
The resource contacted the Hackapp user and he noted that the aforementioned vulnerability is typical for many services, but noted that there is no evidence that this vulnerability was used to access the Stars account.
