SKR terminated investigation of Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Russian Investigative Committee (SCR) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the department's press service.
The decision was made in connection with the death of an aircraft commander and a boarder.
Judicial expertise showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of take-off, the failure of the crew to perform standard landing procedures, as well as the unintended output of the engines to increased direct thrust speeds.
The Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline, which followed the flight Prague-Moscow, was crashed on December 29, 2012 while landing at Moscow Vnukovo Airport.
The aircraft flew out of the runway and burned down.
At the scene of the accident, the commander of the aircraft, the second pilot and a boarding engineer were killed.
Two guides were taken to medical facilities, where they later died from the injuries they received.
Three more men on board, hospitalized with severe bodily injuries, were undergoing long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, which was moving at the time of the accident on the Kiev highway, suffered serious bodily damage.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor's office after the accident conducted a check at Red Wings, during which numerous violations were identified.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed its work in the summer of 2013.
