Anger was the most universal and functional emotion of man.
An angry expression of a face is biologically universal to humanity, and every person involved in its organ and muscle group is not random, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, researchers from Australia and the United States found.
They spoke about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and can be read briefly in a press release from the University of California in Santa Barbara.
Angry expression of the face - moved and dropped down the eyebrows, stretched into the thin line of the lips, swollen nostrils - the same in all cultures, and make it even blind from the birth of children, never seen it, notes the lead author of the study.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, the scientists discovered that this emotion originated to effectively manage disputes during a conflict.
The more physical harm one person can inflict on another, the more opportunity he has to dictate his conditions, and he brings it to the interlocutor by means of anger.
The researchers found evidence and their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more often angry and turn to appliances, consider themselves to have the right to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and also prefer force-based methods of resolving conflicts to peaceful ones.
Turning away from the fact that anger is above all a "trade emotion", the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry expression of the face should represent the angry individual's more powerful and dangerous condition in the eyes of the interviewee - and so on.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled a person on a computer where each of the seven elements of an angry person was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
While the lowered eyebrows or the forward eyebrows individually did not make the face evil, the person depicted with such traits more physically strong participants admitted unanimously.
Human anger, as in animals, poses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own power, forcing one’s consent and submission.
A man inflates his nostrils and squeezes his lips with the same purpose as a fox that inflates, or a baboon that shows his claws.
Anger "starts" by the interlocutor's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, most effectively demonstrating the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most surprising thing is that none of the components of an angry person is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said John Tubby, an anthropologist.
Ministry of Communications offered to allocate 250 million rubles to the television company "Krim"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "Crimea".
This is stated in the draft government decree prepared by the agency, which was introduced by "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating the conditions for the large-scale information illumination of the socio-economic situation and the development of the modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the premises".
In particular, the money allocated is intended to redeploy the hardware-studio unit, video hosts, central hardware and video server.
The acquisition of a mobile TV station and satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of the fiber optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget funds provided for by the Ministry of Communications.
The state-run television broadcaster Crimea was founded in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the television signal coverage of the television company accounts for more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Crimea" Television Company received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
